'''''Mota Coqueiro, ou A Pena de Morte''''' (in {{lang-en|Mota Coqueiro, or The [[capital punishment|Capital Punishment]]}}) is a [[1877 in literature|1877]] [[novel]] by [[Brazil]]ian journalist and writer [[José do Patrocínio]]. It is a semi-fictitious account of the life of the farmer [[Manuel da Mota Coqueiro]], also known as "The Beast of [[Macabu River|Macabu]]", who was sentenced to [[hanging]] in 1852 for a crime he did not commit and executed March 6, 1855 in [[Macaé]], [[Rio de Janeiro state|RJ]].

