'''Structured English Immersion (SEI)''' is a technique for rapidly teaching English to [[English as a Foreign or Second Language|English Language Learners]]. The term was coined by Keith Baker and Adriana de Kanter in a 1983 recommendation to schools to make use of [[Official bilingualism in Canada|Canada's]] successful [[French immersion]] programs.<ref name="Case for SEI">{{cite journal | last = Clark | first = Kevin | authorlink = |date=April 2009 | title = The Case for Structured English Immersion | journal = Educational Leadership | volume = 66 | issue = 7 | pages = 42–46 | publisher = ASCD | location = Alexandria, VA | url = http://www.ascd.org/publications/educational-leadership/apr09/vol66/num07/The-Case-for-Structured-English-Immersion.aspx | format = PDF | accessdate = November 272 2013
}}</ref> The Canadian model was developed to encourage bilingualism through immersing Anglophones in the minority language and replaced [[language policies of the Canadian provinces and territories|many English-only laws in various Canadian provinces]] before the 1960s, while in the United States the same approach was advocated to force minority speakers to adopt English.
More recently, SEI has been defined as a methodology in which English language learners (ELLs) learn English through structured and sequential lessons. Specially developed for ELLs, these lessons are based, to a large degree, on the mainstream curricula. (Haver, Johanna J., ''Structured English Immersion,'' Corwin Press, 2002)
In the 2009 U.S. Supreme Court decision, Horne v. Flores, the majority opinion stated, "Research on ELL instruction indicates there is documented, academic support for the view that SEI is significantly more effective than [[bilingual education]]. Findings of the Arizona State Department of Education in 2004 strongly support this conclusion."<ref>{{cite web|author = SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES |title = HORNE, SUPERINTENDENT, ARIZONA PUBLIC INSTRUCTION v. FLORES ET AL |url = https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/08pdf/08-289.pdf |publisher = SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES |location = Washington D.C. |format = PDF |date = June 25, 2009 |accessdate = June 27, 2009 }}</ref> The chairman of the Center for Equal Opportunity, Linda Chavez, praised the Supreme Court ruling, noting "the failure of bilingual education in performing the number-one job of our public schools, which is to teach children English so they can succeed in 21st century America."<ref>{{cite web |author = Center for Equal Opportunity |title = CEO Praises Supreme Court Decision in Horne vs Flores |url = http://www.ceousa.org/content/view/700/119/ |publisher = Center for Equal Opportunity |location = Falls Church, VA |format = PDF |date = June 26, 2009 |accessdate = June 27, 2009 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716155825/http://www.ceousa.org/content/view/700/119/ |archivedate = July 16, 2011 |df = }}</ref> SEI is mandatory in California, Arizona and Massachusetts where voter initiatives opted to restrict the use of bilingual education in preference for SEI.
== SEI Framework == Only Arizona mandates that its public schools implement SEI models as follows: * Significant amounts of the school day are dedicated to the explicit teaching of the English language, and students are grouped for this instruction according to their level of English proficiency.<ref name="Case for SEI" /> * "The English language is the main content of SEI instruction. Academic content plays a supporting, but subordinate, role."<ref name="Case for SEI" /> * "English is the language of instruction; students and teachers are expected to speak, read, and write in English."<ref name="Case for SEI" /> * "Teachers use instructional methods that treat English as a foreign language."<ref name="Case for SEI" /> * "Students learn discrete English grammar skills."<ref name="Case for SEI" /> * "Rigorous time lines are established for students to exit from the program."<ref name="Case for SEI" /> * SEI program graduates continue to receive support services until they are reclassified as "fluent English proficient" whereby Federal law then requires students be monitored for two years after reclassification.<ref name="Case for SEI" />
== SEI by State == In [[Arizona]], where SEI is required of all schools in the state,<ref>{{cite web |author = Tom Horne (Superintendent of Public Instruction) |title = Guidance on SEI Model implementation for 2009-2010 (letter to Superintendents and Program Administrators) |url = http://www.ade.state.az.us/oelas/downloads/GuidanceonSEIModelImplementationfor2009-2010.pdf |publisher = Arizona Department of Education |location = Phoenix, Arizona |format = PDF |date = May 7, 2009 |accessdate = June 27, 2009 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> all textbooks, materials, and assessments used in an SEI classroom must be aligned to the Arizona K-12 English Language Learner Proficiency Standards<ref>{{cite web |author = Arizona Department of Education |title = Preface to the Arizona English Language Proficiency (ELP) Standards |url = http://www.ade.state.az.us/oelas/downloads/1-FinalPreface-Revised11-09-07.pdf |publisher = Arizona Department of Education |location = Phoenix, Arizona |format = PDF |date = January 9, 2007 |accessdate = June 27, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author = Arizona Department of Education |title = English Language Proficiency (ELP) Standards - Listening and Speaking |url = http://www.ade.state.az.us/oelas/downloads/2-FinalListeningandSpeakingStandards-Revised11-12-07.pdf |publisher = Arizona Department of Education |location = Phoenix, Arizona |format = PDF |date = November 12, 2007 |accessdate = June 27, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author = Arizona Department of Education |title = English Language Proficiency (ELP) Standards - Reading |url = http://www.ade.state.az.us/oelas/downloads/3-FinalReadingStandards-Revised11-12-07.pdf |publisher = Arizona Department of Education |location = Phoenix, Arizona |format = PDF |date = November 12, 2007 |accessdate = June 27, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author = Arizona Department of Education |title = English Language Proficiency (ELP) Standards - Writing |url = http://www.ade.state.az.us/oelas/downloads/4-FinalWritingStandards-Revised11-12-07.pdf |publisher = Arizona Department of Education |location = Phoenix, Arizona |format = PDF |date = November 12, 2007 |accessdate = June 27, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author = Arizona Department of Education |title = Glossary for the Arizona English Language Proficiency (ELP) Standards |url = http://www.ade.state.az.us/oelas/downloads/5-FinalELPGlossary-Revised01-02-08.pdf |publisher = Arizona Department of Education |location = Phoenix, Arizona |format = PDF |date = January 2, 2008 |accessdate = June 27, 2009 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100525092242/http://www.ade.state.az.us/oelas/downloads/5-FinalELPGlossary-Revised01-02-08.pdf |archive-date = 2010-05-25 |dead-url = yes |df = }}</ref> and the Discrete Skills Inventory. The Arizona English Language Learner Assessment (AZELLA) is used to measure English proficiency of SEI students in Arizona.<ref>{{cite web |author = Arizona Department of Education |title = Structured English Immersion Models of the Arizona English Language Learners Task Force |url = http://www.ade.state.az.us/ELLTaskForce/2008/SEIModels05-14-08.pdf |publisher = Arizona Department of Education |location = Phoenix, Arizona |format = PDF |date = May 14, 2008 |accessdate = June 27, 2009 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110102052325/http://www.ade.state.az.us/ELLTaskForce/2008/SEIModels05-14-08.pdf |archivedate = January 2, 2011 |df = }}</ref>
